<body>
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Car Fuel Tank Guide</h1>

    <!-- Purpose Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Purpose</h2>
      <p>The fuel tank is a critical component of a vehicle's fuel system, designed to store and supply fuel to the engine. It ensures a steady flow of fuel while maintaining safety and preventing leaks or contamination.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Components of the Fuel Tank Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Components</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fuel Tank:</strong> A durable container, usually made of metal or plastic, that stores fuel.</li>
        <li><strong>Fuel Pump:</strong> Transfers fuel from the tank to the engine.</li>
        <li><strong>Fuel Level Sensor:</strong> Measures the amount of fuel in the tank and sends data to the fuel gauge.</li>
        <li><strong>Fuel Filler Neck:</strong> The tube through which fuel is added to the tank.</li>
        <li><strong>Vent System:</strong> Allows air to enter and exit the tank as fuel is consumed or added.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- How It Works Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>How It Works</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Fuel is stored in the tank and drawn by the fuel pump when the engine is running.</li>
        <li>The fuel pump sends fuel through the fuel lines to the engine, where it is mixed with air and burned for power.</li>
        <li>The fuel level sensor monitors the amount of fuel in the tank and updates the fuel gauge on the dashboard.</li>
        <li>The vent system prevents pressure buildup or vacuum formation in the tank.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Maintenance Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Maintenance</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Regularly inspect the fuel tank for leaks, rust, or damage and repair or replace it if necessary.</li>
        <li>Check the fuel pump and fuel level sensor for proper operation and replace them if they fail.</li>
        <li>Ensure the fuel filler cap is securely tightened to prevent fuel evaporation and contamination.</li>
        <li>Clean the fuel tank periodically to remove debris or sediment that can clog the fuel system.</li>
        <li>Use high-quality fuel to prevent contamination and extend the life of the fuel system components.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Signs of Fuel Tank Issues Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Signs of Fuel Tank Issues</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fuel Leaks:</strong> Visible fuel puddles under the vehicle or a strong fuel smell.</li>
        <li><strong>Inaccurate Fuel Gauge:</strong> The fuel gauge may show incorrect levels due to a faulty sensor.</li>
        <li><strong>Difficulty Starting:</strong> A clogged fuel tank or failing fuel pump can make it difficult to start the engine.</li>
        <li><strong>Reduced Fuel Efficiency:</strong> A damaged fuel tank or vent system can reduce fuel efficiency.</li>
        <li><strong>Unusual Noises:</strong> A failing fuel pump may produce whining or humming noises.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Images Section -->
